[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The gap in attainme
[normal]nt increases across the Key stages and by 19 it is significant.
[normal] Prior attainment at Key S
[normal]tage 4 impacts on student performance at Key stage 5.
[normal] 
[normal]At Key Stage 5 females attain consistently better than males and White British males are amongst the groups that 
[normal]consistently perform
[normal] 
[normal]less well
[normal]. 
[normal]For one very large group of Leicester young people – White boys – almost one half fail to attain Level Two by age 19 after
[normal] five
[normal] years of secondary education and, for many, a further three years in post-16 education and train
[normal]in
[normal]g 
[normal]The future for these under-attaining groups is bleak
[normal], risking unemployment and low paid work.
[normal](
[normal] 
[normal]A.Suddaby, 
[normal]The Leices
[normal]ter 13-19 P
[normal]artnership board,19 January 2012
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Students will not improve their attainment
[normal] if they are not participating in the education and training system available. In August 2013 13.2% of White British students were NEET. Such pupils who already had low attainment at Key Stage 4 will fall further behind peers the longer the
[normal]y remain NEET (A
[normal].Suddaby, 2012)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Different progression 
[normal]and repetition 
[normal]rates are exhibited by different ethnic groups
[normal] which impact on their attainment at 19
[normal]. 
[normal]90% of Asian females who attain level 2 at 16 progress directly to a level 3 qu
[normal]alification whereas only approximately 50% of White males do so
[normal]. 
[normal]Instead
[normal],
[normal] a
[normal] higher number of White males repeat level 2 qualifications post-16
[normal] (most often by studying a vocational qualification)
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]delaying their entry to level 3 and 
[normal] thus  reducing 
[normal]the pote
[normal]ntial of attaining this level by the age of 19 (
[normal]A.
[normal]Suddaby, 2012 - 
[normal]see Figure Six).
[normal] 
[normal]Two thirds 
[normal]of Asian females who attain Level One at 16 progress to Level Two.  Conversely, only about 20% (one in five) White males make this progression
[normal],
[normal] with four out of f
[normal]ive remaining at Level One
[normal] (A.Suddaby,
[normal] 
[normal]2012)
[normal].  
